Visualize the data

In [5]:
def get_acc(df):
    return df.iloc[:,1:]

def plot_ts(df1,df2,df3,i):
    x=get_acc(df1)
    y=get_acc(df2)
    z=get_acc(df3)
    x_c=x.cumsum(axis=1)
    y_c=y.cumsum(axis=1)
    z_c=z.cumsum(axis=1)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=plt.figaspect(0.3))
    fig.tight_layout()
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1, projection='3d')
    ax.plot(x.iloc[i,:], y.iloc[i,:], z.iloc[i,:])
    ax.set_title('Accelaration')
    
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2, projection='3d')
    ax.plot(x_c.iloc[i,:], y_c.iloc[i,:], z_c.iloc[i,:],c='orange')
    ax.set_title('Velocity')
    plt.show()    

def plot_some_ts(num):
    for i in range(num):
        plot_ts(df1,df2,df3,i)

plot_some_ts(5)

Task B¶

Tranform the data to long format.

In [6]:
def long_format_ts(df1,df2,df3,velocity=False):
    list1=[]
    for idx in range(len(df1)):
        df=pd.concat([df1.iloc[idx,1:] , df2.iloc[idx,1:] ,df3.iloc[idx,1:]],axis=1)
        df.columns=['x','y','z']    
        if velocity==True:
            df['x']=df['x'].cumsum(axis=0)
            df['y']=df['y'].cumsum(axis=0)
            df['z']=df['z'].cumsum(axis=0)
        df['label']=df1.iloc[idx,0]
        df['time series id']=idx  
        df=df.reset_index().rename(columns={'index': 'time index'})
        df=df[['time series id','time index','label','x','y','z']] 
        list1.append(df)    
    return pd.concat(list1)

acc_long_df=long_format_ts(df1,df2,df3)
vel_long_df=long_format_ts(df1,df2,df3,True)

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

def pca_transform(df):
    pca = PCA(n_components=1)
    df['PCA_1D']=pca.fit_transform((df[['x','y','z']]))
    return df

pca_acc=pca_transform(acc_long_df)
pca_vel=pca_transform(vel_long_df)
    
def get_single_ts(df,i):
    return df.loc[df['time series id']==i]

    return df.loc[df['label']==i]

def compare_plots(df,title):
    for i in range(1,9):
        a=get_same_label_ts(df,i) #get time series data with same label
        j1=random.choice(list(set(list(a['time series id'])))) #randomly select a time series id
        s=get_single_ts(a,j1) 
              
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=plt.figaspect(0.4))
        ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1, projection='3d')
        ax.set_title(title + ' of class ' + str(i))
    
        ax.plot(s['x'], s['y'], s['z'],label='3D, Time Series ID = ' + str(j1))
        ax.plot(np.zeros(len(s))+4,np.arange(len(s)),s['PCA_1D'],label='1D, Time Series ID = ' + str(j1))

        j2=random.choice(list(set(list(a['time series id'])))) 
        s=get_single_ts(a,j2)
        
        ax.plot(s['x'], s['y'], s['z'],label='3D, Time Series ID = ' + str(j2))
        ax.plot(np.zeros(len(s))+4,np.arange(len(s)),s['PCA_1D'],label='1D, Time Series ID = ' + str(j2))
             
       
        j3=random.choice(list(set(list(a['time series id'])))) 
        s=get_single_ts(a,j3)
        
        ax.plot(s['x'], s['y'], s['z'],label='3D, Time Series ID = ' + str(j3))
        ax.plot(np.zeros(len(s))+4,np.arange(len(s)),s['PCA_1D'],label='1D, Time Series ID = ' + str(j3))
        ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2)      
       
        plt.show()


compare_plots(pca_acc,'Acceleration')
compare_plots(pca_vel,'Velocity')

Comparasion between plots. I plotted in 3D format. This makes it possible to observe the real data and transformed data (PCA) at the same time. The PCA data is plotted by denoting a constant for the dimension x. This way it acts like 2D in a 3D setting.

As seen from the graphs, when we decrease the dimension by PCA, we can plot two dimensional plots. However, plots don't show any similarities compare to their 3d versions in terms of shape. When we look at two dimensional plots, we can see that they follow some characteristics. In other words, time series in the same class mostly have similar two dimensional graphs. For instance, Accelearation of class 1 2 and 8, plots look very similar to each other. When we look at different classes, we see peeks and valleys at different times compare to other classes. However is not very easy to distinguish classes by just looking at two dimensional graphs.

Task C¶

Apply PCA to all classes.

def get_pca_info(df,n): #returns PCA summary for n th component.
    pca = PCA(n_components=n)
    pca.fit(df[['x','y','z']])
    pca_info = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_)
    pca_info['explained_variance'] = pca.explained_variance_
    pca_info['explained_variance_ratio'] = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
    pca_info['cumulative_explained_variance_ratio'] = pca.explained_variance_ratio_.cumsum()
    return pca_info.iloc[[n-1]]  


def pca_info_wrt_labels(df,n): #return PCA summary for all classes 
    dic = {i:get_pca_info(get_same_label_ts(df,i),n) for i in range(1,9)}
    dic['benchmark']=get_pca_info(df,n)
    
    df1=pd.DataFrame(pd.concat(dic.values()))
    df1['label']=dic.keys()
    df1.set_index('label',inplace=True)
    df1.columns=[str(n)+'_component_x',str(n)+'_component_y',str(n)+'_component_z','explained_variance','explained_variance_ratio','cumulative_explained_variance_ratio']
    return df1

acc_pca_info_wrt_labels_c1=pca_info_wrt_labels(acc_long_df,1)

In here benchmark represents PCA information without filtering data into classes. If we look at the explained variance ratios, we see that in most of the cases it is greater than the bechmark. It is expected to obtain this result, since if classes shapes are different, then their orthogonal bases should also be different. By setting best bases we can explain more of the variance in the our sample. It is important to note that when we filter data our sample size decrease as well. So for components explained variance ratio doesn't represent the whole data. Another finding is that y eigenvalue of the component 1 is more stable compare to x and z.

Task D¶

Obtain symmetric distance matrix.

In [27]:
from sklearn.metrics import pairwise_distances

def get_labels(df):
    return df.iloc[:,0]

def get_pairwise_distance(df1,df2,df3,cumsum=False,n=1):
    if cumsum==True:
        df1=df1.iloc[:,n:].cumsum()
        df2=df2.iloc[:,n:].cumsum()
        df3=df3.iloc[:,n:].cumsum()
        n=0
    x_dist=pairwise_distances(df1.iloc[:,n:])
    y_dist=pairwise_distances(df2.iloc[:,n:])
    z_dist=pairwise_distances(df3.iloc[:,n:])    
    return x_dist+y_dist+z_dist

acc_total_dist = get_pairwise_distance(df1,df2,df3)
vel_total_dist = get_pairwise_distance(df1,df2,df3,cumsum=True)

from sklearn.manifold import MDS

def apply_mds(data):
    model = MDS(n_components = 2,dissimilarity='precomputed',n_jobs=-1)
    return model.fit_transform(data)

acc_mds=apply_mds(acc_total_dist)

Visualize MDS.

In [42]:
def visualize_data(data,labels):
    sc=plt.scatter(data[:, 0], data[:, 1],
            c=labels, edgecolor='black', alpha=0.6,
            cmap=plt.cm.get_cmap('Spectral', 8))
    plt.colorbar(sc)

visualize_data(acc_mds,get_labels(df1))

In here, we follow a different method. Instead of PCA, we look at the distance between instances. However, by only looking at the graph it is difficult to distungish classes. For instance, it is impossible to separate Class 1 and Class 6. Class 7 is the most observable class in the data. Moreover, we can obtain which classes are far distanant from each other. For example, class 5 and Class 2 are far distant from each other.
